body:
I'm not convinced of this design in general for the input/output styles forcing the involvement of so many scattered template files.  It seems quite unnecessarily complicated.

Can you explain why the following does not work:

```
{ macro: input_area(cell) }
{ block input_block }
{ if prompt_style == 'ipython' }
    { if bw: }
        {block in_ipython_bw}
    { else: }
        {block in_ipython}
    { endif }
{ else if prompt_style == 'python' }
    { if bw: }
        {block in_python_bw}
    { else: }
        {block in_python}
    { endif }
{ else: }
    {block custom_in }
{ endif }
{ endblock }
{ endmacro }
```

and a similar macro for output.  This seems dramatically simpler than having all of these mixin templates that redefine things, and I tested a similar model in a custom template, and it seemed to work fine.

I recall something said during the meeting about not allowing unused blocks, but in testing, this doesn't appear to be true. You can have plenty of unvisited blocks, it happens pretty much every time a notebook is rendered.
